<div id="node-303" class="node node-blog_post">


  <h2><a href="../../blog-posts/following-copenhangen-accord-china-submits-carbon-intensity-target-unfccc-secretariat" title="Following the Copenhagen Accord: China Submits Carbon Intensity Target to UNFCCC Secretariat">Following the Copenhagen Accord: China Submits Carbon Intensity Target to UNFCCC Secretariat</a></h2>

      <span class="submitted">Posted by Deborah Seligsohn on Feb 1, 2010</span>
  
  <div class="content clear-block">
    <div class="field field-type-filefield field-field-image">
    <div class="field-items">
            <div class="field-item odd">
                    <img src="../../files/chinainfo/imagecache/news-image/UN&#32;flags.jpg" alt="" title="" width="160" height="120" class="imagecache imagecache-news-image imagecache-default imagecache-news-image_default"/>        </div>
        </div>
</div>
<p>As provided for in last month‚Äôs <a href="http://unfccc.int/resource/docs/2009/cop15/eng/l07.pdf">Copenhagen Accord</a>,  China has now submitted its ‚Äúmitigation actions‚Äù (click <a href="../../library/chinas-submission-mitigation-actions-copenhagen-accord">HERE</a> to see the text of the letter in our ChinaFAQs Library).  While there was much speculation as to which actions China would submit, in the end China has reported the full set of measures first announced by <a href="../../blog-posts/president-hus-un-speech-key-signal-chinese-domestic-policy-will-be-more-carbon-focused">President Hu Jintao</a> at the United Nations in November 2009, and then amplified by the <a href="../../blog-posts/chinas-state-council-unveils-40-45-carbon-intensity-target">State Council decision</a> on the 40-45% carbon intensity target at the end of November.</p>
  </div>
<div class="clear-block">
    	<div class="readmore"> <a href="../../blog-posts/following-copenhangen-accord-china-submits-carbon-intensity-target-unfccc-secretariat">Read more</a> </div>
  </div>

  <div class="clear-block">
    <div class="meta">
        </div>

          <div class="links"><ul class="links inline"><li class="node_read_more first last"><a href="../../blog-posts/following-copenhangen-accord-china-submits-carbon-intensity-target-unfccc-secretariat" title="Read the rest of Following the Copenhagen Accord: China Submits Carbon Intensity Target to UNFCCC Secretariat.">Read more</a></li>
</ul></div>
      </div>

</div>
<div id="node-301" class="node node-blog_post">


  <h2><a href="../../blog-posts/chinese-premier-wen-leads-new-energy-policy-coordinating-body" title="Chinese Premier Wen Leads New Energy Policy Coordinating Body">Chinese Premier Wen Leads New Energy Policy Coordinating Body</a></h2>

      <span class="submitted">Posted by Deborah Seligsohn on Jan 28, 2010</span>
  
  <div class="content clear-block">
    <p>The Chinese government <a href="http://uk.reuters.com/article/idUKTOE60Q09720100127">announced today</a> that Premier Wen Jiabao will lead a new Energy Coordinating body.    Wen will chair the committee, which will include Executive Vice Premier Li Keqiang and <a href="http://china.globaltimes.cn/chinanews/2010-01/501647.html">ministers of 21 different departments</a>.</p>
  </div>
<div class="clear-block">
    	<div class="readmore"> <a href="../../blog-posts/chinese-premier-wen-leads-new-energy-policy-coordinating-body">Read more</a> </div>
